snippet.textDisplay:
Ronny, awesome vid. Although I'd probably disagree with the tuning statement where you said you can't tune for efficiency. Generally you can pick 2 of the 3 and sacrifice the 3rd...
Power, Efficiency, Emission.
Go Power and Emission you sacrifice Efficiency.
Go Power and Efficiency and you sacrifice Emision.
Go Efficiency and Emission and you sacrifice Power.
I'm no expert by any throw of the rock, but thats how I understand the tuning process.

snippet.textDisplay: There's absolutely nothing wrong with wheel spacers as long as you are buying a reputable brand that bolts onto the hub. Its essentially the same as changing your offset. Now is it a good idea, of course not. You should get proper wheels and not run any sort of spacer ideally. But I've ran wheel spacers for over 2 years and never had an issue. You just need to make sure everything is torqued to spec, which is a pain in the ass.

snippet.textDisplay: When I was a young fella , I made the biggest mistake by trying to make my daily driver into a mud truck . I had a perfectly good 3/4 ton Dodge which I decided to put a 6 suspension lift and a 2 inch body lift on it to fit 38 inch Super Swamper mud tires . I learned fast that highway driving was dangerous because the truck wandered so badly , plus I got about 8 miles to the gallon . I also found out winter driving was all but impossible as well , because big chunky bias plies are horrible in the snow and ice . The only benefit was it looked cool and ran the mud good , but a daily driver it was not by any stretch of the imagination .

snippet.textDisplay:
Wheel spacers.... wheel spacers. A lot can be said about them. They are OKAY if done right. For example if you put a larger tire size on, one that is also a little fatter you might find you're rubbing your frame and you've lost a few degrees turning radius.

This is where spacers come into play, and are Actually useful- however you ONLY want to space it the amount required to prevent rubbing, and you also want to use billetted aluminum spacers made by a proper company.

I've run spacers for years now because going from 31OD to 34OD tires definitely caused some serious frame rub.

And you mentioned "buying the proper diff that sorts out the track", unfortunately not all vehicles have compatible diffs that will do that. Fortunately here in the states with my Nissan N50 (same platform as the D40) you can put Nissan Titan suspension components on it which will give you 3" more space each side without spacers- essentially long travel but it solves the frame rub as well! (And gives you +10" (+25cm) of wheel travel per tire instead of the stock 5.5" (14cm).


That said, as you said- torque specs are DEAD important with spacers.

snippet.textDisplay:
16" rim max on 33" tyres, and 18" on 35". Anymore than that and not only does your car look like hot shit, but you lose out on performance on and off road with extra un-sprung weight and less grip and malleability. Cheap ass lights and accessories also look like shit, because if you have "KINGS" all around your car it announces that you're cheap, floor your POS through every red light, and get bogged pulling out of the driveway. The bullbars like the one on the Patrol look like shit too, get a proper bullbar. If you own a Jeep, Navara or anything IFS, good luck. Petrol IS the inferior option, and auto's are like turning the difficulty to toddler and the fun to 0.
Also, if you don't have proper recovery points all round or a proper recovery block in the hitch, if you ever get bogged, your car should be left stranded right where it is. I wouldn't pull a car out by the hitch, I've seen others do it and either the strap breaks or falls off, or the hitch ball snaps off and goes flying. If you're going to go off road properly, get the right gear first.

snippet.textDisplay: I think people who drag around a hi lift and can’t or don’t know how or don’t have points to use it is stupid.  If it’s bling it goes! But I love my hi lift it’s so nice I can lift on my sliders or front/rear hi clearance bumpers and have done all.  It’s mounted on my bed rack ready to go.  I do have to clean it and lube it but it is something I WONT live without.  I also bring a full set of Milwaukee cordless tools They are heavy and bulky, but when you need it you need it.  Wheel spacers are the same as offset wheels our Tacoma’s can’t run 33’s without dragging on UCA without one or the other both kill bearings wreck steering and breaking but it’s a necessary evil.  Next set of tires I’m going back to 32’s with AT. Instead of MT I’ve decided I just don’t need them that much but you have to learn that.  I will miss them on occasion I am sure. I actually drove the truck recently without the spacers and didn’t like how much more tippy it felt and put them right back on.  They can be safe but they are harder to maintain, like anything you have to take care of it.  If you leave your truck in a poor state it WILL leave you in a poor state.  Before we go on trips we inspect and look over this stuff.  Pull wheels, spacers, check brakes; cv’s, u joints, wheel bearings, belts, batteries.  I carry spares of all of the above except battery.  And someone in the group is carrying a hydraulic floor jack and stands.
